meta {
  name: POST SPIN challenge (step 1 of NA two-step SPIN handshake)
  type: http
  seq: 5
}

post {
  url: https://b-h-s.spr.{{country}}00.p.con-veh.net/ss/v1/user/{{user_id}}/challenge
  body: json
  auth: bearer
}

auth:bearer {
  token: {{access_token}}
}

body:json {
  {}
}

headers {
  Accept: application/json
  Content-Type: application/json
  User-Agent: MyVW/1.0 Android
}

docs {
  v2.10.0 (Group C). VW North America SPIN challenge endpoint.

  Step 1 of the two-step SPIN verification flow that NA uses for any
  privileged remote action (unlock, doors, alarm clear, etc).

  Response shape:

    {
      "data": {
        "challenge": "abcd1234..."
      }
    }

  Defensive key-name variants observed across firmware generations:
  ``challenge`` / ``nonce`` / ``challengeData``. The Python parser
  walks all three in priority order.

  NA-specific shape vs EU:

  - EU CARIAD-BFF accepts the raw SPIN in the action payload directly
    (e.g. ``POST /vehicle/v1/.../lock body: {action: unlock, spin: 1234}``).
  - NA refuses that pattern on post-2024 Cox firmware. Instead, the
    client must fetch a per-user single-use challenge nonce, hash
    ``SHA1(SPIN + nonce)`` (uppercase hex), and POST the response back
    to the companion ``/spin`` endpoint to receive a short-lived
    ``sessionToken``. That token is then presented as the
    ``X-Spin-Session`` header on the action request itself.

  Pattern verified against the matpoulin reference + a smali excerpt
  from the MyVW APK.
}
